<doc id="46676" wikidata="Q220680" url="?curid=46676" title="Banach fixed-point theorem">
<text>In mathematics, the Banach fixed-point theorem (also known as the contraction mapping theorem or contractive mapping theorem or Banach–Caccioppoli theorem) is an important tool in the theory of metric spaces; it guarantees the existence and uniqueness of fixed points of certain self-maps of metric spaces and provides a constructive method to find those fixed points. It can be understood as an abstract formulation of Picard&#x27;s method of successive approximations. The theorem is named after Stefan Banach (1892–1945) who first stated it in 1922.

==Statement==
&quot;Definition.&quot; Let formula_1 be a metric space. Then a map formula_2 is called a contraction mapping on &quot;X&quot; if there exists formula_3 such that
:formula_4
for all formula_5
Banach fixed-point theorem. Let formula_1 be a non-empty complete metric space with a contraction mapping formula_7 Then &quot;T&quot; admits a unique fixed-point formula_8 in &quot;X&quot; (i.e. formula_9). Furthermore, formula_8 can be found as follows: start with an arbitrary element formula_11 and define a sequence formula_12 by formula_13 for formula_14 Then formula_15.

&quot;Remark 1.&quot; The following inequalities are equivalent and describe the speed of convergence:

:formula_16

Any such value of &quot;q&quot; is called a &quot;Lipschitz constant&quot; for formula_17, and the smallest one is sometimes called &quot;the best Lipschitz constant&quot; of formula_17.

&quot;Remark 2.&quot; formula_19 for all formula_20 is in general not enough to ensure the existence of a fixed point, as is shown by the map
:formula_21
which lacks a fixed point. However, if formula_22 is compact, then this weaker assumption does imply the existence and uniqueness of a fixed point, that can be easily found as a minimizer of formula_23, indeed, a minimizer exists by compactness, and has to be a fixed point of formula_24 It then easily follows that the fixed point is the limit of any sequence of iterations of formula_24

